Adoption is for the benefit of BOTH parent and child.<br>
<br>
Certainly, if you asked someone who wanted to adopt why they wanted to adopt, one of their reasons might be to give a good home to a child who otherwise might be neglected.  But just as likely is the reasoning that they actually want a child because it provides some emotional benefit for them.  <br>
<br>
For example, a number of studies indicate that african american children are less likely to be adopted than white children.  This offers some evidence that potential adoptive parents are not purely concerned about the welfare of children as children. If this was the case, racial preferences would not exist.<br>
<br>
A counter to this would be that some people might think that african american children would be harmed if they had white parents.  But the reality of this logic is that african american children will not be adopted at all.  This is hardly in the best interest of the child.<br>
<br>
Adoption agencies already investigate potential adoptive parents before entrusting them with a child.  This process can be used to screen gay parents as well.  Using stereotypes of gay couples in an effort to hold them to a more stringent adoption process, thus treating similarly situated individuals differently, violates Equal Protection.<br>
<br>
Of course that our Supreme Court is hostile to hearing dometic issues (Ie, domestic violence, marriage, and adoption) means that it is unlikely it would say the same thing any time soon. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=itchibumbashalots>ItchibumBashalots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Hated One</span><br>  Posts: 983<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/4/03 2:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=831.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Case Against Same-Sex Marriage...</span><hr size=1> I disagree that it isnt about kids....because that is what is should be about.<br>
<br>
Like I said.  The evaluation process should be equal...but as you include gay couples....it would have to be a whole new evaluation system...one that also met many of the differences that gay couples would have vs non gay.  For example...does Bob dress in drag during the work week?  Is Bob going to be dropping little Billy off at school?  How will this affect Billy's ability to be accepted at school?  Get my point?<br>
<br>
It is different.  On the whole...if each child could be placed in a safe heterosexual environment...that would be my choice.  But I also will not ignore the fact that there are many gay couples out there who would make great parents.  My cousin would be a great Dad...I have no doubt...but he leads a permiscuous life....many partners some who are flamboyantly gay....and how would the adopted childs friends react to that?  Would he be able to keep friends?  Would he be ostrosized(sp) at school?<br>
<br>
It may be argued that its societies fault for not being more accepting but that is besides the point.  It is about kids.... how placing them one place vs another affects their chance at a stable &quot;normal&quot; (however you want to define that....i expect comment) upbringing that allows them to be happy and successful in life.  A child will have no choice in the matter....should he or she be placed in a situation that they will have to defend for the rest of their childhood?  Is that fair to the child?<br>
<br>
