<br>
The situation with regards to adoption vs. divorced is somewhat complicated, actually.  Some adoptive parents, especially in lesbian and gay couples, are the partners of the kids' biological parents.<br>
<br>
However, since most states did not allow gay or lesbian adoptions until recently, and many still do not, I'd presume that most of the households studied were gay and lesbian parents who already had kids.<br>
<br>
This winds up leading to the second point.  Most courts presume the mother's going to be the better parent, so more women wind up with the kids after a divorce than men.  Sometimes, courts will recognize the claim that homosexuality is grounds for declaring one of the two parents unfit.  This compounds the legal problems for a gay father gaining custody of his kids.  It's not surprising that if the sample of parents are primarily the gay and lesbian biological parents, then most of those households are lesbian, given the judicial system's tendency to give mothers custody. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=syllestraefv>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 3873<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/4/03 5:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=831.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Case Against Same-Sex Marriage...</span><hr size=1> I'm a heterosexual male.   Our son was born in February.  I can tell you this... people will unintentionally make you feel like you're wierd for being affectionate with your kid.<br>
